<div class="hero">
  <div class="case-type">Environment · Systems · World State</div>
  <h1>Weather & Time-of-Day System</h1>
  <p class="hero-desc">A full weather cycle with weighted random selection, precipitation particles, ambient audio, sky tweening, indoor detection via raycasting, and per-player temperature lerping driven by time-of-day.</p>
  <div class="meta-row">
    <div><div class="meta-label">Timeline</div><div class="meta-value">2024 — Ongoing</div></div>
    <div><div class="meta-label">Language</div><div class="meta-value">Lua / Luau</div></div>
    <div><div class="meta-label">Platform</div><div class="meta-value">Roblox Studio</div></div>
    <div><div class="meta-label">Type</div><div class="meta-value">Personal Project</div></div>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="content">
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">The Problem</div>
    <h2>A living world needs more than a skybox swap</h2>
    <p>Most games with "weather" simply swap a skybox. The goal was a fully simulated world state — weather that affects temperature, audio, visuals, terrain color, and player experience simultaneously, driven by a real time-of-day cycle.</p>
    <div class="callout"><strong>Design goal:</strong> Weather should feel like a real system — weighted probability, smooth transitions, environmental consequences, and player-aware effects like indoor detection.</div>
  </div>
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">Time-of-Day Cycle</div>
    <h2>A real clock driving world attributes</h2>
    <p>The TOD cycle runs on <strong>RunService.Heartbeat</strong>, incrementing a clock each frame scaled to the configured day/night lengths (3 min day, 6 min night). <code>Lighting.ClockTime</code> updates every frame for accurate sun positioning. A parallel coroutine sets workspace attributes (<strong>TimeOfDay</strong>, <strong>DayOrNight</strong>) based on the current hour, which all other systems listen to reactively.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">Weather Selection</div>
    <h2>Weighted random weather that never repeats back-to-back</h2>
    <p>Each weather type has a configured weight. The roll function builds a cumulative probability range, picks a random float, and returns the matching weather. The current weather is always excluded so the same type never repeats consecutively. <strong>Sunny</strong> is flagged daytime-only — if rolled at night it falls back to Clear automatically.</p>
<pre><code><span class="kw">local function</span> <span class="fn">rollWeather</span>(excludeWeather)
    <span class="kw">local</span> totalWeight = <span class="nm">0</span>
    <span class="kw">for</span> name, data <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">pairs</span>(weatherConfig) <span class="kw">do</span>
        <span class="kw">if</span> name ~= excludeWeather <span class="kw">then</span> totalWeight += data.weight <span class="kw">end</span>
    <span class="kw">end</span>
    <span class="kw">local</span> range = <span class="fn">math.random</span>() * totalWeight
    <span class="kw">local</span> acc = <span class="nm">0</span>
    <span class="kw">for</span> name, v <span class="kw">in</span> <span class="fn">pairs</span>(weatherConfig) <span class="kw">do</span>
        <span class="kw">if</span> name ~= excludeWeather <span class="kw">then</span>
            acc += v.weight
            <span class="kw">if</span> range <= acc <span class="kw">then</span> <span class="kw">return</span> name <span class="kw">end</span>
        <span class="kw">end</span>
    <span class="kw">end</span>
<span class="kw">end</span></code></pre>
  </div>
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">Client Effects</div>
    <h2>Sky, atmosphere, precipitation, audio, and terrain</h2>
    <p>On weather change the client tweens <strong>Atmosphere</strong> and <strong>Clouds</strong> to the new values over 3 seconds, swaps the Sky asset, and adjusts SunRays for sunny weather. For rain and snow, a <strong>SkyPart</strong> welded to the player's HumanoidRootPart emits particles above them. A raycast fires upward every 0.5s — if a roof is detected, emitters disable and ambient audio volume drops, simulating being indoors. Snow tweens tagged terrain parts to white via CollectionService and reverts on weather change.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-label">Temperature System</div>
    <h2>Per-player temperature lerping</h2>
    <p>Each weather type offsets the base temperature. The TOD cycle adds random variance — warmer at noon, cooler at night. When the workspace Temperature attribute changes, each player's character attribute lerps toward the target on Heartbeat at a configurable rate. Any in-progress lerp is cancelled before a new one starts to prevent conflicts.</p>
    <div class="tag-list">
      <span class="tag">Lua</span><span class="tag">RunService</span><span class="tag">TweenService</span><span class="tag">CollectionService</span><span class="tag">Raycasting</span><span class="tag">Particle Effects</span><span class="tag">Ambient Audio</span>
    </div>
  </div>
